## How the compiler finds promise_type

When the compiler sees a coroutine function with return type `R` and arguments `Args...`, it looks up `promise_type` through:

```cpp
std::coroutine_traits<R, Args...>::promise_type
```

By default, `coroutine_traits` takes `R::promise_type` — which is why we declare `promise_type` as a nested type of the return class. Specializing `coroutine_traits` directly is rarely needed (e.g., to add support for third-party types).

## Six required methods of promise_type

### 1. get_return_object()

```cpp
Generator get_return_object() {
    return Generator{coroutine_handle<promise_type>::from_promise(*this)};
}
```

Called first when the coroutine starts. Must construct the return-type object (the one the caller receives). Key point: `coroutine_handle::from_promise(*this)` turns a reference to the `promise` object inside the frame into a handle — a lightweight pointer to the entire frame.

### 2. initial_suspend()

```cpp
std::suspend_always initial_suspend() noexcept { return {}; } // lazy start
std::suspend_never  initial_suspend() noexcept { return {}; } // eager start
```

Determines what happens immediately after the frame is created — before the coroutine body starts running. `suspend_always` → the coroutine is created but **does not start**; the first `resume()` launches it. `suspend_never` → the coroutine starts **immediately**. Generators almost always use `suspend_always` (lazy initialization).

### 3. final_suspend()

```cpp
std::suspend_always final_suspend() noexcept { return {}; }
```

Called after the coroutine body finishes (reached the end or a `co_return`). **Must be `noexcept`.** Almost always returns `suspend_always`: the coroutine pauses at the final point, allowing you to safely read `done()` and then call `destroy()`. Returning `suspend_never` would auto-destroy the frame, after which the handle must not be touched.

### 4. yield_value(T)

```cpp
std::suspend_always yield_value(T value) noexcept {
    current_value = value;
    return {};
}
```

Called by the compiler at each `co_yield expr`. Receives the value, stores it (so the caller can read it via `handle.promise().current_value`), and returns an awaitable — usually `suspend_always` to suspend the coroutine.

### 5. return_void() / return_value(T)

```cpp
void return_void() noexcept {}          // for co_return; or end of function
void return_value(T v) { result = v; }  // for co_return expr;
```

The choice between them determines whether the coroutine supports `co_return expr`. Both cannot be defined simultaneously in the same `promise_type`.

### 6. unhandled_exception()

```cpp
void unhandled_exception() { std::terminate(); }         // simple but harsh
void unhandled_exception() { exc_ = std::current_exception(); } // store and rethrow later
```

Called if an exception propagates out of the coroutine body. The call happens inside a `catch` block, so `std::current_exception()` returns the current exception. Usually either terminate the program (`terminate`), or store an `exception_ptr` to rethrow later from the iterator.

## coroutine_handle::from_promise and promise()

```cpp
// Get a handle from a promise (inside promise_type itself):
auto h = std::coroutine_handle<promise_type>::from_promise(*this);

// Get the promise from a handle (externally):
promise_type& p = h.promise();
```

This pair is the bridge between the "controlling" part (the handle) and the "value-storing" part (the promise).

## RAII and lifetime management

The coroutine frame is heap-allocated on call and must be destroyed exactly once via `handle.destroy()`. The correct pattern is to wrap the handle in an RAII owner:

```cpp
~Generator() { if (handle_) handle_.destroy(); }
Generator(const Generator&) = delete;           // forbid copy
Generator& operator=(const Generator&) = delete;
Generator(Generator&& o) noexcept               // allow move
    : handle_(std::exchange(o.handle_, {})) {}
```

`std::exchange(o.handle_, {})` transfers the handle and zeroes the source — the standard move idiom for resources.

## Iterator for range-for

For `Generator<T>` to work in `for (auto v : gen)`, it needs `begin()` and `end()`. C++20 allows using `std::default_sentinel_t` paired with an iterator that has `operator==(default_sentinel_t)`:

```cpp
iterator begin() {
    handle_.resume(); // advance to first co_yield
    return iterator{handle_, handle_.done()};
}
std::default_sentinel_t end() { return {}; }
```

```cpp
struct iterator {
    std::coroutine_handle<promise_type> handle;
    bool done;

    iterator& operator++() {
        handle.resume();
        done = handle.done();
        return *this;
    }
    T operator*() const { return handle.promise().current_value; }
    bool operator==(std::default_sentinel_t) const { return done; }
};
```

On early exit (`break`) from range-for, the `Generator` destructor is called immediately — and `handle_.destroy()` correctly releases the frame even if the coroutine has not finished.

